{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e9a7790a-f7a3-43b4-960e-cb46852951d0","content":"This is a known .NET platform compatibility issue. Here's what's happening:\n\n## Root Cause\n\n**Apple's cryptographic frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) do not support DSA.** In earlier .NET versions, DSA on macOS worked via an OpenSSL backend. Microsoft has been progressively removing support for legacy crypto algorithms — DSA classes were marked `[Obsolete]` starting in .NET 7, and the platform-specific OpenSSL fallback on macOS has been dropped, causing `DSA.Create()` to throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`.\n\n## Fix Options\n\n**1. Migrate to a modern algorithm (preferred long-term fix):**\n   Re-sign with ECDSA or RSA. DSA is cryptographically weak by modern standards.\n\n**2. Use BouncyCastle for legacy verification (if you must keep DSA):**\n\n```csharp\n// dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey)\n{\n    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\n    signer.Init(false, pubKey);\n    signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\n    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\nBouncyCastle is a fully managed implementation — no native crypto dependency, so it works on all platforms.\n\n**3. Conditional runtime check (short-term guard):**\n\n```csharp\nif (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n{\n    using var dsa = DSA.Create();\n    // ...\n}\nelse\n{\n    // Fall back to BouncyCastle on macOS\n}\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** Use BouncyCastle for DSA signature *verification* of legacy data across all platforms for consistency, and plan to migrate to ECDSA/RSA for any new signing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b804380-1e03-475b-a34e-91d628d4b8b6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, and more significantly in later versions, Microsoft has been deprecating and removing older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically:\n\nIn .NET 7, DSA on macOS was already not supported by the platform (Apple's Security framework/CommonCrypto doesn't support DSA). In earlier .NET versions, there was a managed/OpenSSL-based fallback, but Microsoft has been tightening this.\n\n\nThe core issue is that macOS's native crypto libraries never supported DSA, so older .NET versions relied on OpenSSL bindings as a workaround. Starting in .NET 7, calling `DSA.Create()` on macOS throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` because .NET removed those OpenSSL fallbacks and Apple platforms don't natively support DSA.\n\nFor the .NET 10 to .NET 11 transition specifically, I don't have detailed information about what's changed between those versions since we're looking at very recent releases.\n\nBut the broader pattern is clear: .NET has been systematically removing DSA support, especially on macOS where Apple's native frameworks don't support it. Earlier versions relied on OpenSSL as a fallback, but that's been phased out. The issue you're hitting—DSA.Create() failing on macOS after upgrading—fits this pattern of deprecation and removal of legacy cryptographic algorithms.\n\nThe practical solutions are to either use BouncyCastle for a managed DSA implementation, switch to a modern algorithm like ECDSA or RSA, or call OpenSSL directly through P/Invoke if you absolutely need DSA.","outputTokens":1371,"requestId":"E029:386D1F:5833A36:60B6FBD:69F4063B"},"id":"b16a7aeb-545b-43d0-b0cb-a3a728bbdfa8","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:48:12.256Z","parentId":"62b8ae86-6527-4092-8500-047f5cf53e87"}
